{"type":"message","id":"0fe54f43","parentId":"acabfb54","timestamp":"2026-04-10T08:05:46.036Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The DELETE works directly. The issue in my script is the `api()` function - it returns `{ status, data }` where `data` is the parsed JSON body. For DELETE, the API returns the commit object with status 200, not 204. Let me check what my DELETE function returns. The issue is probably that the status code is 200, not 204, and my function checks for `200 && 200`.Wait, my check was `if (r.status !== 200 && r.status !== 204) throw new Error(...)`. The status should be 200, so it should pass. But maybe the API is returning 422 from the script because of the SHA format. \n\nLooking at the raw curl request, it's definitely sending the right SHA value, so the problem must be elsewhere in my script's implementation. I'm looking at my DELETE handler logic and it seems correct—it accepts both 200 and 204 status codes. The real problem might be that `sha` is coming back as undefined from the listDir call, which would make my request payload invalid even though the curl equivalent worked fine.\n\nChecking my walkDir function, I notice it filters out `node_modules`, `.git`, and `dist`, but `sha` isn't being returned in the listing results, so that can't be the culprit. The 422 error from GitHub's API typically means the SHA was missing or invalid in the request, but I just confirmed sha is present in the actual DELETE call. I'm wondering if this is a timing issue—the API might be caching the directory listing and not returning current SHA values. Let me just test deleting a few files directly with curl first to isolate the problem.\n\nActually, I think I've found it. When I list the root directory, the files come back as an array, but when I list a specific path, GitHub returns a single object instead. The SHA should still be there in both cases, so let me trace through my recursive deletion function to see where the request is actually failing.\n\nI'm checking my DELETE logic and it looks correct—I'm validating the SHA exists before trying to delete, and handling both success status codes properly. The SHA is definitely being returned from the listDir call, so that's not the issue. Let me just run a simpler test to see what's actually happening.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"单个删除是通的。简化脚本直接执行：\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_db2t1htlr8ee_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"curl -s -H \"Authorization: Bearer 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\" \\\n  \"https://api.github.com/repos/wangyang962996947/yaxins/contents/\" 2>&1 | python3 -c \"\nimport json,sys\nitems = json.load(sys.stdin)\nprint(f'共 {len(items)} 项:')\nfor i in items: print(f'  {i[\\\"type\\\"]:4s} {i[\\\"name\\\"]:30s} sha:{i.get(\\\"sha\\\",\\\"\\\")[:12]}')\"","timeout":10}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"miaoda","model":"miaoda-model-auto","usage":{"input":145003,"output":650,"cacheRead":7163,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":152816,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775808315588,"responseId":"chatcmpl-b3bd119d-e385-4203-b3f7-ad7eb5e50440"}}
