{"type":"message","id":"c324c7a0","parentId":"8c5663fc","timestamp":"2026-04-10T08:11:35.448Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The tree API didn't work as expected - it's showing the old files mixed with the new files. The issue is that git tree uses the base tree and only adds new files, but the base tree already had all the old files. The approach of using `createTree` with `base_tree` only creates a NEW tree with the changes, but the tree object in Git contains ALL files (the new ones), not just the diff.\n\nActually, I think I misunderstand the git tree API. The `base_tree` parameter is used to compute a diff, not to include files from it. So when I create a tree with `base_tree` but only provide the new files, the new tree only contains those new files - the old files should NOT be in the new tree.\n \nBut looking at the actual directory listing, I'm still seeing all the old directories like HARNESS-AGENT and agents. This suggests the commit operation itself worked, but I'm looking at the wrong tree - the listing is probably showing the combined contents from the parent commits rather than just what was in my new commit. I think I see the issue now - when I create a tree, I'm only passing the new files and their blobs, but the base tree's structure isn't being preserved, so the resulting tree only contains my new files without the old directory structure. So my approach is wrong - I need to preserve the parent tree structure while only modifying the specific files I want to change.\n\nLet me try a different strategy: instead of trying to selectively update files in the tree, I'll just force push a completely new tree that only contains the code-scanning-plugin directory with all its files. I need to rethink this - the git tree API works differently than I initially understood. When I create a new tree with a base tree and new entries, the API computes the difference and only includes files that actually changed, ignoring files from the base tree that aren't in my new entries. So if I create a tree with just `projects/code-scanner-plugin/...` entries using an empty base tree, it should give me exactly what I want - only those files, not all the old ones. I see the issue now—the API listing shows all files from the repository's root, but those old directories like `HARNESS-AGENT` and `agents` shouldn't exist if my tree only contains the new files. I need to verify what the actual tree SHA contains, because something doesn't add up here. Hmm, but the directory listing shows all the old directories... Maybe the API endpoint is showing the current state of the repository (HEAD commit), but the current HEAD still includes the old files from previous commits? \n\nWait no - if I updated the `main` branch to a new commit, the HEAD should be the new commit. Unless... the old files were pushed in a previous session that didn't complete, or the `push-via-api.mjs` script ran after the `reset-repo.mjs` somehow.\n\nActually, I think the issue might be that the previous push via API created a commit with all 85 files, and when I ran `reset-repo.mjs`, it was based on that commit (which had all the old files). The new commit I created only contains 17 new blobs, but since I'm updating the main branch to this new commit, the listing should only show those 17 files.\n\nLet me think through the git tree API more carefully. When I create a tree with a base_tree and provide new entries, the API creates a new tree by starting from the base tree and then applying only my changes. So if the base tree contains old directories like `agents/` and `HARNESS-AGENT/`, and I don't provide entries for them in my new tree, those old directories should still appear in the result. But I'm creating a new tree with just the 17 new files from my project directory and using the base tree, so those old directories shouldn't be in the new tree. The issue is that the API response is showing all the old files, which suggests something went wrong with how I'm creating or applying the tree changes. I see the issue now—the `createTree` API doesn't preserve files from the base tree by default. When I pass entries with paths like `DESIGN.md` and `server/mockMinio.ts`, it's computing a diff from the base tree and only including files that actually changed. So the resulting tree only contains the 17 new files I explicitly added, not the 85 files from the base tree. Those other directories and files must have been in an earlier commit that I'm no longer building on. I think I see it now—the `createTree` call didn't specify a `base_tree` parameter, so it's creating an entirely new tree from scratch with just the 17 files, ignoring what was in the parent commit. But the directory listing is still showing those old directories from before, which doesn't add up if I'm truly replacing the tree completely.\n\nLet me actually inspect what files are in this new tree to figure out what's really going on.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_f4udh0iljhvf_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# 查看新 commit 的 tree 内容\ncurl -s -H \"Authorization: Bearer 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\" \\\n  \"https://api.github.com/repos/wangyang962996947/yaxins/git/trees/528b346e2bd8740b902584a8abd562ab3bba79db?recursive=1\" 2>&1 | python3 -c \"\nimport json,sys\nd=json.load(sys.stdin)\nprint(f'Tree SHA: {d[\\\"sha\\\"]}')\nprint(f'Truncated: {d.get(\\\"truncated\\\")}')\nprint(f'共 {len(d[\\\"tree\\\"])} 个条目:')\nfor i in d['tree']: print(f'  {i[\\\"type\\\"]:4s} {i[\\\"path\\\"]}')\"","timeout":10}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"miaoda","model":"miaoda-model-auto","usage":{"input":152528,"output":1253,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":153781,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775808645460,"responseId":"chatcmpl-ef727567-9bcd-4a10-a46c-c6c57ad10741"}}
