{"type":"message","id":"8a82bbef","parentId":"58efd467","timestamp":"2026-04-10T08:50:04.168Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good progress! 8/11 tests pass. The 3 failures are all related to the same issue: B6. 等待结果(轮询): Step 4 未出现.\n\nThe key issue: `testPollingLogic` passes - the seed worked and we can read the file from port 9000. But `testMinioSeedAndWaitResult` fails after 20 seconds - Step 4 didn't appear.\n\nThis means: `waitForResult` in the frontend is NOT detecting the file. Why?\n\nLet me think about this:1. The frontend calls `submitScanTask` which POSTs to `http://localhost:3001/api/scan/submit`2. \n\nThe submission succeeds and returns immediately with a 202 status. Then `waitForResult` starts polling - it calls `fileExists(uuid)` which sends a HEAD request to `http://localhost:9000/{uuid}`. The seed was written to the same file path that `fileExists` checks, so the file should be found. Let me trace through `mockMinioClient.ts` to see how `fileExists` actually works.\n\nIt sends a HEAD request to the mock minio server, which checks if the file exists locally and returns a 200 status. If the seed was successful and we verified the file exists at the correct path, then `fileExists` should return true. So why isn't the step changing?\n\nLet me check the URL - the test submits to `http://localhost:3001/api/scan/submit`, but the mock minio client is connecting to `http://localhost:9000`. The frontend server is on port 5174, so requests from the browser to `localhost:3001` and `localhost:9000` should work fine.\n\nActually, I think the real issue might be with the CORS or HEAD request handling in the mock minio server.\n\nLooking at the mock server code, when handling a HEAD request, it checks if the file exists and returns 200 with content-length if it does, or 404 if not. The 404 response is missing the CORS headers though - that might be the problem.\n\nThe fetch on the frontend is running in a browser context with CORS enabled, so a missing `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` header on the 404 response could cause the fetch to fail. Let me trace through the actual flow: the test uses `fetch()` which is Node.js fetch, not browser fetch, so CORS shouldn't matter there. But the real issue is the browser is making the request to `http://localhost:9000`, not Node.js.\n\nI should add CORS headers to the 404 response and verify that the mock minio server is actually running on port 9000 when the test executes. I'm checking the request flow more carefully—the seed logic passes and writes to `/tmp/code-scanning-mock/{uuid}`, then `waitForResult` polls `fileExists(uuid)` which calls `HEAD http://localhost:9000/{uuid}`. Since both use the same `DATA_DIR`, the file should be found, but something's preventing the file from being detected on the second poll.\n\nLooking at the HEAD response handler, it doesn't send CORS headers on the 404 case, which might cause the browser to fail the request—but that would throw an error, not silently return false. Let me trace through the actual logic again: the file gets seeded, we verify it's readable via GET, but then `fileExists` keeps returning false on subsequent polls. I need to add logging to `mockMinioClient.ts` to see what `HEAD` is actually returning, or better yet, have the test verify `fileExists(uuid)` directly after seeding to confirm whether the HEAD request is working as expected. Actually, the cleanest approach is to wait for the natural backend delay—after the 60-second timeout completes, the backend will seed the file to port 9000, which is where `waitForResult` is polling from. This way I'm testing the actual flow end-to-end without relying on the seed endpoint.\n\nBut waiting 60 seconds per test run adds up, so I need to find a way to verify the logic without that delay. Let me think about whether there's a way to shorten the wait time in the test itself, or just accept the 60-second wait as part of the test suite. Or maybe the issue is something else entirely—let me trace through what happens when the backend calls `uploadTextFile(uuid, report)` to see if there's a different problem I'm missing.\n\nThe backend's `uploadTextFile` sends a PUT request to `localhost:9000/{uuid}`, which the mock minio server handles by writing the file to `/tmp/code-scanning-mock/{uuid}`. Then when `waitForResult` polls with a GET request, it should find the file and return successfully. But the seed is injected at a different path, so maybe there's a mismatch in how the UUID is being used or stored between the backend and the mock server.\n\nLet me just run the full 60-second test and see if it actually works end-to-end.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"seed 后文件确认可读，但轮询不触发 Step 4。调试一下 `fileExists` 在 Playwright 中的实际返回：\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_h1je6sf02efc_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/gem/workspace/agent/workspace/projects/code-scanning-plugin/src/mockMinioClient.ts","newText":"/** 检查文件是否存在 */\nexport async function fileExists(objectName: string): Promise<boolean> {\n  try {\n    const res = await fetchRetry(`${MOCK_BASE}/${objectName}`, { method: 'HEAD' })\n    return res.ok\n  } catch {\n    return false\n  }\n}","oldText":"/** 检查文件是否存在 */\nexport async function fileExists(objectName: string): Promise<boolean> {\n  try {\n    const res = await fetchRetry(`${MOCK_BASE}/${objectName}`, { method: 'HEAD' })\n    return res.ok\n  } catch {\n    return false\n  }\n}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"miaoda","model":"miaoda-model-auto","usage":{"input":106622,"output":1262,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":107884,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775810960318,"responseId":"chatcmpl-cb7f6127-8bbf-4a77-b39c-24a870de5abf"}}
